                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.94114A O.T./9–2144: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Switzerland</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harrison</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bern</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-09-21T22:00:00+01:00"
                            >September 21, 1944—10 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received September 22—8:35 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>6274. American Interests—Indochina. Legation’s 5069, August 7.<note n="80"
                        xml:id="d1015fn80">Not printed.</note> Note September 19 from Foreign Office
                    states Swiss Consulate, Saigon, reports unofficially advised that 1861 POWs
                    detained Saigon camp include 209 Americans. Camp leader is Captain J. H. Fowler.
                    According a detained officer, treatment satisfactory. Japanese Commanding
                    Officer correct.</p>
                <p>About 430 patients in hospital where dangerous and cruel soldier in charge.
                    Insufficient supplies given doctors who lack anti-tetanous serum, morphine,
                    pills and syringes.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harrison</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
